{% import "product-components.njk" as pc %}
<section class="intro-section mb-12">
  <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Web Realtime</strong> is the home for the <strong>open-app realtime transport</strong> &mdash;
    the live server&rarr;client channel an <em>open</em> app holds: presence, live data, collaborative
    cursors, server-pushed updates. It owns a single <strong>transport-negotiation protocol</strong> that
    auto-picks the best available channel so an app declares <em>realtime delivery</em> once and never
    hand-wires a socket. Minted in
    <a href="/backlog/455-server-to-client-delivery-transport-home-by-purpose-vs-by-me/">#455</a> (Fork 2),
    which settled the transport home <strong>by purpose</strong>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Transport negotiation is a <strong>Protocol, not an intent</strong>. Choosing SSE vs. WebSocket vs.
    WebTransport vs. long-poll is async, capability-dependent, and swappable &mdash; the same shape as a
    guard or push provider, never UX vocabulary. The native-first anchors are <strong>SSE</strong> and
    <strong>WebSocket</strong>; <strong>WebTransport</strong> is capability-gated (Chrome/Edge only, no
    Safari) and <strong>long-poll/poll</strong> is the degradation floor that always works. A
    <code>CustomTransportProvider</code> seam lets a hub (Socket.IO, SignalR, Centrifugo) plug in behind
    one contract.
  </p>

  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(8, 145, 178, 0.08); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #0891b2; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #0e7490; font-size: 1rem;">Not push — the by-purpose split</h4>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      <a href="/projects/webnotifications/">Web Notifications</a> owns <strong>closed-app push</strong> (a
      service worker woken by a push service after the tab is gone). Web Realtime owns the
      <strong>open-app</strong> live channel. The two are <strong>non-fungible</strong>: you do not fall
      back from a live socket to a closed-app push &mdash; they survive opposite lifecycles &mdash; so
      <a href="/backlog/455-server-to-client-delivery-transport-home-by-purpose-vs-by-me/">#455</a> gave
      each its own home rather than forcing one transport abstraction over both.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

